  "prompt": "Is battery water just the distilled water? If yes, can we use the water condensed by ACs or filtered by RO systems for inverter batteries?",
  "response": "Battery water, commonly used in lead-acid batteries such as those in inverters, is indeed distilled water. Distilled water is preferred because it is free from minerals and impurities that could affect the performance and lifespan of the battery.\n\nRegarding the use of water condensed by air conditioners (ACs) or filtered by reverse osmosis (RO) systems:\n\n1. **AC Condensed Water**: The water condensed by air conditioners can contain various impurities depending on the environment in which the AC operates. This water may have dust, pollen, and other airborne particles. While it is possible to use AC condensed water if it is further purified (e.g., distilled), using it directly is not recommended due to potential contaminants.\n\n2. **RO Filtered Water**: Reverse osmosis water is generally free from many impurities, but it may still contain some minerals and other dissolved solids. RO water is not as pure as distilled water, which is why it's generally not recommended for use in batteries without additional purification.\n\n**Recommendation**: For the best performance and longevity of your inverter batteries, it is advisable to use distilled water. If you choose to use RO water or AC condensed water, make sure it is further purified through distillation to ensure it meets the required standards for battery water.",
